node.text:
I bought this watch from the grandson of the original owner.  He was able to provide a short but interesting history about this rare Constellation watch. “My grandfather is from Transylvania (when it belonged to Hungary). He is a Magyar. He ended up being very big in Romanian politics and was in prison for many years as a political prisoner. He helped liberate Romania from the Iron Guard. He and my grandmother actually met in prison, my grandmother was jailed at a very early age. He remained in Romania all his life until his death in the late 80's.” .
.
.
.
.
.

.

node.text:
{please scroll over to compare both dial examples} ~ I am unsure why some people LOVE to go on someone else’s post and judge about their watches.  Does it makes them feel better?  The problem is, these guys love to judge without any proper knowledge to back themselves.  Anyhow, when it comes to a black dial watch, I would say about 95% of the time, it is a redial.  But before you claim that one is a redial, make sure you are 100% firm.  On today’s post, I have two different factory original finish black dial.  In this first image, I have this gilt (gold font) font matte painted black dial.  Notice how the black paint is on the side of the indexes?  The reason for that is, if you flip over the dial you can see that there is no index feet anywhere.  This is called a fixed index feet dial and why the paint covers the side of each index.  On the second photo, when you turn over that dial you can see all the index feet holes/position.  In this situation, the indexes will never show paint or plating on their side.
